haeology.com/author/freiburg/">University of Freiburg</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/griffith/">Griffith University</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/plos/">PLOS</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/penns/">University of Pennsylvania</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/wright/">Mathew Wright</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/fmuseum/">Field Museum</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"></div></div><!-- end item --><div class="item clearfix"><h4><a href="https://popular-archaeology.com/author/hawass/">Dr. Zahi Hawass</a></h4><div class="author-list-bio"><p>Zahi Abass Hawass is an Egyptian archaeologist, Egyptologist, and former Minister of State for Antiquities Affairs, serving twice. He has also worked at archaeological sites in the Nile Delta, the Western Desert, and the Upper Nile Valley.</p>
